Think carefully through the trade-offs between statistical anomaly detection (z-score, IQR, MAD-based methods) and machine learning-based anomaly detection (Isolation Forest, LSTM autoencoders, Prophet with anomaly scoring) specifically for the case of small time series with 50-500 data points. This is the typical case for a performance analysis tool that receives a batch of recent metrics, not a streaming system with millions of data points.

Statistical methods have several advantages at small sample sizes: they require no training data, they have interpretable results (this value is 4.2 standard deviations from the mean), they make distributional assumptions explicit, and they are computationally trivial. Their weakness is that they assume stationarity and unimodal distributions, both of which latency data routinely violates.

ML-based methods can theoretically model seasonality and multimodal distributions, but with 50-500 points, you cannot reliably fit an Isolation Forest without overfitting, and LSTM models require thousands of sequences to generalize. Prophet requires at minimum dozens of periods of the seasonal component to work well.

Think through the following specific scenarios and argue which detection family is better for each: a sudden step-change in P99 latency after a deployment (no seasonality involved), a gradual drift in P50 latency over 48 hours, a regular weekly latency spike every Monday morning, and a bimodal latency distribution where cache hits cluster around 5ms and cache misses cluster around 200ms.

Then think through the hybrid approach: using statistical methods for immediate anomaly detection and ML methods for baseline establishment when sufficient historical data exists. What are the failure modes of the hybrid approach? When does having a stale ML baseline become worse than using a simple rolling statistical baseline? What data volume threshold should trigger switching from statistical to ML-based baseline computation?
